40. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spuler" authorityYear="1910" box="[184,361,1610,1637]" class="Insecta" family="Epermeniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="131" pageNumber="132" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Epermeniidae</taxonomicName>
– fringe-tufted moths
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="132" pageNumber="133" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="132.[140,1108,167,510]" pageId="132" pageNumber="133">
Minute to small (
<quantity box="[335,448,167,193]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" unit="mm" value="13.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="6.0">6–20 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with narrow, fringed wings, usually with one or more tufts of erect scales. Th ey can be separated from other small, narrowwinged moths by the presence of large spines on the metatibiae (not restricted to the dorsal surface as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fletcher" authorityYear="1929" box="[358,586,272,299]" class="Insecta" family="Schreckensteiniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Schreckensteiniidae</taxonomicName>
). Known larvae begin life as concealed feeders, feeding externally in later instars.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="132.[140,1108,167,510]" pageId="132" pageNumber="133">
Worldwide, 83 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spuler" authorityYear="1910" box="[472,628,343,369]" class="Insecta" family="Epermeniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Epermeniidae</taxonomicName>
are known, from all regions; 11 are known from North America. Five species are known from AB, and a sixth is expected to be found here. The group was revised recently by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaedike R" box="[656,836,413,439]" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" pagination="301 - 302" refId="ref246104" refString="Gaedike R (1977) Revision der nearktischen und neotropischen Epermeniidae (Lepidoptera) [Revision of the Nearctic and Neotropical Epermeniidae (Lepidoptera)]. Beitrage Zur Entomologie 27: 301 - 302." type="journal article" year="1977">Gaedike (1977)</bibRefCitation>
, but the descriptions are brief and the illustrations poor. Two more species were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Gaedike R" box="[921,1104,448,474]" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" pagination="57 - 64" refId="ref246242" refString="Gaedike R (2008) New species and records of the Nearctic Epermeniidae (Lepidoptera). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 151: 57 - 64." type="journal article" year="2008">Gaedike (2008)</bibRefCitation>
. Th ree AB species were illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pohl GR &amp; Bird CD &amp; Landry J-F &amp; Anweiler GG" box="[552,754,483,510]" pageId="132" pageNumber="133" pagination="61 - 82" refId="ref261706" refString="Pohl GR, Bird CD, Landry J-F, Anweiler GG (2005) New records of microlepidoptera in Alberta, Canada. Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 59: 61 - 82." type="journal article" year="2005">Pohl et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
